l estate developer and politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|SC|5|South Carolina's 5th congressional district}} since 2017. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he was a [[South Carolina House of Representatives|South Carolina House Representative]] from 2005 to 2007 and from 2009 until 2017.<ref>[http://www.scstatehouse.net/members/bios/1421590739.html South Carolia House] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20041227042152/http://www.scstatehouse.net/members/bios/1421590739.html |date=2004-12-27 }}, Ralph Norman biography.</ref> \n\nIn February 2017, Norman vacated his seat to launch a [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district special election, 2017|U.S. congressional bid]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Marchant|first=Bristow |url=http://www.thestate.com/news/politics-government/article133163614.html |title=SC legislator resigns seat to run in special 5th District congressional race |publisher=The State |date=2017-02-16 |accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref> Norman won the [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district special election, 2017|2017 5th congressional district special election]], assuming office in the U.S. House of Representatives in June 2017.\n\n==Early life and career==\nHe was born in [[York County, South Carolina]], and currently resides in [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]], where he is a real estate developer at the Warren Norman Company, a business founded by and named after Norman's father. He and his wife, Elaine have 4 children and 16 grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n==South Carolina House of Representatives==\nIn 2004, Norman was elected to serve District 48 in the South Carolina House of Representatives, winning a three-way Republican primary outright with 52% of the vote. After one term, Norman chose not to run for reelection so he could become the 2006 Republican candidate in an unsuccessful bid for U.S. Congress in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]] against [[John Spratt]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyman|first1=Rick|title=Seeing Plausible Target, Republicans Take Aim at a Democratic Seat in South Carolina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/14/us/14sprat.html|work=The New York Times|date=April 14, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2009, Ralph Norman defeated Democrat Kathy Cantrell in a special election to reclaim his old seat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norman Returned To SC State House {{!}} FITSNews|url=https://www.fitsnews.com/2009/11/04/norman-returned-to-sc-state-house/|work=FITSNews|date=November 4, 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013023421/http://www.fitsnews.com/2009/11/04/norman-returned-to-sc-state-house/|archivedate=October 13, 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n[[File:Ralph Norman in Rock Hill, SC 5-15-17.jpg|thumb|Norman during his 2017 campaign]]\n\n====2017 special election====\n{{main|South Carolina's 5th congressional district special election, 2017}}\nIn December 2016, Norman announced that he would run for the [[United States House of Representatives]] for [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]] seat of [[Mick Mulvaney]], who joined the Trump administration, in the [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district special election, 2017|2017 special election]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Marchant|first=Bristow |url=http://www.thestate.com/news/politics-government/article130421754.html |title=What happens after SC's Mulvaney gets Trump's budget job? |publisher=The State |date=2017-02-02 |accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2017, Norman won a runoff election against [[Tommy Pope (politician)|Tommy Pope]] for the Republican nomination for the 5th congressional seat of South Carolina. Norman defeated Pope by only 200 votes, with Norman tallying 17,755 votes, and Pope receiving 17,552 votes. Norman faced the Democratic nominee, Archie Parnell, in the June 20, 2017 special election, which he narrowly won with 51% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election Results: Norman Advances in Race for South Carolina's Fifth Congressional District|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/south-carolina-house-special-election-primary-runoff|work=The New York Times|date=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the primary video surfaced of floor debate between Ralph Norman and challenger Tommy Pope discussing a bill to allow police officers to be treated for PTSD under Worker's Compensation. Ralph Norman stated, \"Any one of us could get a crayon and coloring book and start coloring and chewing on the desk and we would be deemed mentally incompetent and we would get paid \u2013 there would be no ending to it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ijr.com/the-response/2017/06/895044-watch-candidate-mulvaneys-congressional-seat-mocked-injured-cops/|title=Watch: Candidate for Mulvaney's Congressional Seat Mocked Injured Cops|date=2017-06-09|work=IJR - Independent Journal Review|access-date=2017-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nNorman was sworn into office on June 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Dumain | first1=Emma | title=South Carolina U.S. House Delegation Now Complete with Swearing-In of Republican Ralph Norman | url=http://www.postandcourier.com/politics/south-carolina-u-s-house-delegation-now-complete-with-swearing/article_30accf94-5ac1-11e7-9f28-a790988f9a15.html | date=June 26, 2017 | publisher=''[[The Post and Courier]]'' | accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Norman joined the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Firearms incident ==\nWhile at a public meeting for constituents on April 6, 2018, Norman engaged in a conversation with representatives from [[Moms Demand Action for Gun Sense in America]] (MDA).<ref name=\"jlovegrove@postandcourier.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/u-s-rep-ralph-norman-pulls-out-loaded-gun-in/article_ea97bda0-39d3-11e8-b120-3b253f2be91e.html|title=U.S. Rep. Ralph Norman pulls out loaded gun in constituent meeting to make point about safety|last=jlovegrove@postandcourier.com|first=Jamie Lovegrove|work=Post and Courier|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref>  During that conversation, Norman placed his personal [[.38|.38-caliber]] [[Smith & Wesson]] [[handgun]] on the table to illustrate his belief that \"gun violence is a spiritual, mental or people issue, not a gun issue.\"<ref name=\"jlovegrove@postandcourier.com\"/>  According to Norman, the loaded firearm was visible for \"maybe a minute, or two minutes\" and was never pointed at any individual.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/latest-news/article208184124.html|title=Congressman Ralph Norman pulls out loaded gun at Rock Hill meet-and-greet|work=heraldonline|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  However representatives from MDA who were seated at the table with Norman, said the firearm was visible for \"five to 10 minutes\" and that they felt unsafe.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/08/us/politics/ralph-norman-gun.html|title=South Carolina Congressman Pulls Out Gun at a Meeting With Voters|last=Stevens|first=Matt|date=2018-04-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-11|last2=Caron|first2=Christina|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/06/politics/ralph-norman-loaded-gun-sc-congressman/index.html|title=Congressman pulls out gun to make point on violence|last=CNN|first=Annie Grayer,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> Norman holds a Concealed Weapons Permit issued by the [[South Carolina|State of South Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/2018/04/06/congressman-ralph-norman-pulls-out-loaded-gun-rock-hill-meet-and-greet/495089002/|title=Congressman Ralph Norman pulls out loaded gun at Rock Hill meet-and-greet|work=The Greenville News|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe incident sparked widespread criticism of Norman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/article208234199.html|title=Some question legality of Rep. Norman gun display at meet-and-greet|work=heraldonline|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref>  On April 9, 2018, [[South Carolina Democratic Party]] Chairman Trav Robertson wrote a letter to the [[South Carolina Law Enforcement Division]] requesting felony charges against Norman for his conduct.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/dems-seek-charges-after-sc-congressman-displays-handgun/479172433/|title=Dems seek charges after SC congressman displays handgun|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> The case was originally assigned to South Carolina 16th Solicitor Kevin Brackett.  However, Brackett recused himself citing a \"personal friendship\" with Norman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/news/state/south-carolina/article208387839.html|title=The Latest: Solicitor recuses self from congressman gun case|work=heraldonline|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref>  The issue was then forwarded to [[Alan Wilson (South Carolina politician)|South Carolina Attorney General Alan Wilson]], who declined to press charges stating that Norman's actions did not \"warrant a criminal investigation\" or constitute \"a proscutable offense.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/04/10/us/ap-us-congressman-gun-south-carolina.html|title=Top Prosecutor: No Gun-Related Charges for SC Congressman|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2018-04-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/37925050/ag-alan-wilson-will-not-charge-congressman-who-pulled-out-gun-during-constituent-meeting|title=AG Alan Wilson will not charge congressman who pulled out gun during constituent meeting|last=Turnage|first=Jeremy|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Sexual assault joke ==\nOn September 20, 2018, at an election debate for the Republican nomination for the 5th congressional seat of South Carolina, Norman joked about [[sexual assault]] allegations made against Supreme Court nominee [[Brett Kavanaugh]]. He kicked-off the debate asking the audience, \u201cDid y\u2019all hear this latest late-breaking news on the Kavanaugh hearings? \u2026[[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] came out saying she was groped by Abraham Lincoln.\u201d <ref>{{cite news|last1=Thebault|first1=Reis|title=GOP congressman jokes about Ruth Bader Ginsburg being groped \u2014 by Abraham Lincoln|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/09/20/gop-congressman-jokes-about-ruth-bader-ginsburg-being-groped-by-abraham-lincoln/|work=The Washington Post|date=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://norman.house.gov/ Congressman Ralph Norman] official U.S. House website\n* [https://www.electralphnorman.com/ Campaign website] \n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/South_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ralph_Norman_%5BR-5%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ralphnorman}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=N000190 | congress=ralph-norman/N000190 | fec=H8SC05158 | votesmart=47930/ralph-norman-jr  }}\n* [https://archive.is/20041227042152/http://www.scstatehouse.net/members/bios/1421590739.html Official Biography, South Carolina House of Representatives]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sc-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=Becky Richardson}}\n{{s-ttl|tit